<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="412" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="412" type="mainText">
Diagnosis. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Myrmoteras" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="412" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Myrmoteras</taxonomicName>
ant with the following diagnostic characters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="412" type="mainText">1 Labrum coneshaped (Mo5), in full frontal view only the basal part with the most raised point with the insertions of the trigger hairs visible.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="412" type="mainText">2 Trigger hairs present (Fig. 3, Mo5).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="412" type="mainText">3 Mandibles with the apical part bent ventral (Fig. 3).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="412" type="mainText">4 Frontal sulcus absent or at most feably developed (Fig. 34).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="412" type="mainText">5 Body with an iridescent shine.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="412" type="mainText">Characters 1 and 2 are autopomorphies of this subgenus (Moffett,, 1985)</paragraph>
